fference a matter of law, resulting in a divide that favors forms of religion authorized by those in power and excludes other ways of being and belonging. In exploring the dizzying power dynamics and blurred boundaries that characterize relations between "expert religion," "governed religion," and "lived religion," Hurd charts new territory in the study of religion in global politics.A forceful and timely critique of the politics of promoting religious freedom, Beyond Religious Freedom provides new insights into today's most pressing dilemmas of power, difference, and governance.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aFreedom of religion. 0aReligion and international relations. 0aReligion and politics. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / International Relations / General.2bisacsh  aAlevis.  aAlevism.  aCentral Africa.  aCold War.  aGuatemala.  aIndia.  aMyanmar.  aNorth Africa.  aRohingya.  aSahrawi refugees.  aSouth Sudan.  aTurkey.  aUnited States.  adevelopment assistance.  aexpert religion.  afaith.  aforeign policy.  aglobal politics.  agovernance.  agoverned religion.  ainterfaith dialogue.  ainternational law.  apolitical projects.  areligion.  areligiosity.  areligious discrimination.  areligious diversity.  areligious engagement.  areligious freedom.  areligious minorities.  areligious minority.  areligious persecution.  areligious practice.  areligious protection.  areligious reform.  areligious rights.  areligious tolerance.  areligious violence.  asocial difference.  asocial tension.  atransnational humanitarianism.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311066592540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781400873814zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degru